bug.short_desc: ScrollComposite with list inside does not scrolls.

long_desc.thetext:
The problem is caused by the ScrollComposite and the fact that is does have flexible height.
As a quick fix please call:
qx.bom.element.Style.set(list.getContainerElement(), "max-height", "200px");
I will have a look at the bug.

This issue is going to be deeper as it appears I guess. I figered out some errors while working with dynamic lists inside ScrollComposite. Sometime it scrolls but not to the end of lists when I change number of records in list data model. Please also check this behavour. I've noticed about this while ago in http://bugzilla.qooxdoo.org/show_bug.cgi?id=7085 but this bug is still not really fixed.
(In reply to comment #1) > The problem is caused by the ScrollComposite and the fact that is does have > flexible height. > > As a quick fix please call: > > qx.bom.element.Style.set(list.getContainerElement(), "max-height", "200px"); > > I will have a look at the bug.

I reproduced your problem...
There are two things that prevent the list from scrolling: 1: if you want to use the ScrollComposite as Page Default you have to deactivate the iScroll container of the page. See _createScrollContainer method
2: You have to assign a VBox layout to the page, for making sure the scrollComposite does get a calculable height.
http://tinyurl.com/axky7ot

To make sure we'r talking about same - I'm using ScrollComposite in some different way as widget container inside page. For my purposes for example I'm using two ScrollComposite objects with List objects inside so I may have both lists on screen at once. So I actually using nested ScrollComposites. Assigning VBox layout to ScrollComposite takes no effect - http://tinyurl.com/a6remok
(In reply to comment #3) > I reproduced your problem... > > There are two things that prevent the list from scrolling: > 1: if you want to use the ScrollComposite as Page Default you have to > deactivate the iScroll container of the page. > See _createScrollContainer method > > 2: You have to assign a VBox layout to the page, for making sure the > scrollComposite does get a calculable height. > > > http://tinyurl.com/axky7ot

The VBox Layout is just one step. You also have to make sure, that there is no iScroll on the page.
Could you please provide a screenshot?
Created attachment 1239 Two List in ScrollComposite put on master page

Ok, now i see your context...
Did you already try the trick with setting the max-height?
qx.bom.element.Style.set(scroll.getContainerElement(), "max-height", "200px");
My first quick fix was assigned to the wrong element.
http://tinyurl.com/d7hl6de

In my case I'm using addCssClass("instance-list") for ScrollComposite container with this addon style:
.instance-list { width: 100%; height: 200px; }
i guess this is almost same?
(In reply to comment #7) > Ok, now i see your context... > > Did you already try the trick with setting the max-height? > > qx.bom.element.Style.set(scroll.getContainerElement(), "max-height", "200px"); > > My first quick fix was assigned to the wrong element. > > http://tinyurl.com/d7hl6de
Yes this is the same. Does it fix your problem?

If we'r talking about this one (7271) - that's not a fix I guess but just kind of trick as you said. Why not fix behaviour instead proposing tricks? I'm sure this kind of tricks will fail in future releases. This trick allows to get UI working as expected but does NOT fix issue described in initial sample.
If we'r talking about (7085) - no it still buggy but it's closed for some reason. And list.getLayoutParent().scrollTo(0, 0) call still fails. Try to modify initial sample and make sure.
Also I'm going to open another bug I guess but I guess it's related to both 7271 and 7085. ScrollComposite calculates wrong height when I change List data model. Try to create such kind of controll ScrollComposite+List inside and play around with List model number data records.
(In reply to comment #9) > Yes this is the same. Does it fix your problem?

First I needed to know if it fix your problem, then I decide how to solve it in the framework.
The ScrollComposite needs a container height and it is not a trick that you set the height you want to apply.
The only convenience I can implement further is to provide a property for the height.

Let's say "yes" - specifying ScrollComposite height is fixing scrolling issue.
(In reply to comment #11) > First I needed to know if it fix your problem, then I decide how to solve it in > the framework. > > The ScrollComposite needs a container height and it is not a trick that you set > the height you want to apply. > > The only convenience I can implement further is to provide a property for the > height.
Closed all bugs already shipped with a release.
